Write Additional Tests for the MegaNav

We’ve used the Cypress Component Testing UI and worked with an existing test.

Now let’s get some practice with the Cypress API by writing some additional MegaNav tests from scratch.

Simulate User Events with Cypress Real Events

As mentioned earlier, Cypress doesn’t fully implement all of the necessary user events.

There’s a package called cypress-real-events that adds support for events like pressing keys, swiping, and more.

The Tab key event in particular is important for accessibility testing that mimics browser behavior. The full list of supported events can be found on their GitHub page.

The workshop repo already has the package installed and configured, as seen in cypress/support/commands.js :

import "cypress-real-events/support"
import "cypress-real-events/support"

Check out the Cypress Real Events GitHub repo for more information.

Adding a “Closed Submenus Should Not Be Reachable” Test

When elements aren’t properly hidden, a keyboard user will still have to tab through them. For this test, we want to make sure that items in a submenu that isn’t open are not able to be reached with the tab key.

Planning the Test

The links inside of a MegaNav submenu are located in the SubNavLinkGroup component located inside of the components/meganav directory.

Looking at the code for the component we can see that when the link items are mapped over, a data-testid attribute is added and given a value that includes the index:

// inside subnav-link-group.js
const SubNavLinkGroup = ({headerText = '', items = []}) => {
    return (
			...
            <ul>
            {items.map((item, index) => (
                <li className="megamenu-submenu-link" key={index}>
                    <a
                        className="nav-link"
                        data-testid={`link-${index}`}
                        href={item.url}
                    >
                        {item.name}
                    </a>
                </li>
            ))}
            </ul>
			...
// inside subnav-link-group.js
const SubNavLinkGroup = ({headerText = '', items = []}) => {
    return (
			...
            <ul>
            {items.map((item, index) => (
                <li className="megamenu-submenu-link" key={index}>
                    <a
                        className="nav-link"
                        data-testid={`link-${index}`}
                        href={item.url}
                    >
                        {item.name}
                    </a>
                </li>
            ))}
            </ul>
			...

We need to write a test that makes sure that when the menu is closed and the tab key, we should not be focused on an element with a data-testid of link-0.

That is where focus would go if the menu was open.

Writing the Test

Below the keyboard operation test, add a new it() block. I’ll use “submenus should not be reachable when closed” for the description, then add the empty arrow function:

it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {

})
it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {

})

For this test I’ll use cy.get() with the same selector to get the first SubNavButton in the MegaNav.

I’ll chain on focus() and realPress('Tab') from Cypress Real Events to focus the button and simulate the tab key being pressed.

Once we have the button and have hit tab, we can assert that the focused item should not have a data-testid of link-0.

Here’s what the test looks like all together:

it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().should('not.have.attr', '[data-testid="link-0"]')
  })
it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().should('not.have.attr', '[data-testid="link-0"]')
  })

When we run Cypress Component Testing, the test passes.

To see if it fails, try removing the data-testid attribute from the SubNavLinkGroup component.

The test still passes.

We have written a tautological test that passes no matter what!

This is the issue mentioned earlier.

Fixing the Tautological Submenu Test

In our first pass at the test, we told Cypress that an attribute should not be present.

We can make the test better by adding in an attribute that should be present.

When we are focused on the first button in the closed MegaNav and we hit the Tab key, focus should move to the second top-level button.

So in our test I’ll add an assertion that the focused element should be a button with an attribute of data-testid with a value of megamenu-section2.

To make sure that Cypress has finished focusing on the element, we’ll use a Promise by chaining a .then() with the assertion inside of the callback function.

This requires us to use a slightly different API than we’ve used before.

Instead of using should() with a string of have.attr , we pass the $el reference from the Promise callback into expect() and chain to.have.attr().

The first argument is a string of the attribute we’re looking for, followed by the value we expect.

Since hitting tab should take us to the second button in the MegaNav, we’ll pass in data-testid and megamenu-section2.

Here’s what the test looks like now:

it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().should('not.have.attr', '[data-testid="link-0"]')

    cy.focused().then(($el) => {
      expect($el).to.have.attr('data-testid', 'megamenu-section2')
    })

  })
it('submenus should not be reachable when closed', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().should('not.have.attr', '[data-testid="link-0"]')

    cy.focused().then(($el) => {
      expect($el).to.have.attr('data-testid', 'megamenu-section2')
    })

  })

Now when we run the test, it passes as expected.

🛠 Challenge: Write a Test for Reaching Submenu Items with the Keyboard

Referencing the tests we’ve written so far, write a test for keyboard reachability of the links inside of an open submenu.

If you get stuck, the Cypress UI’s step-by-step feature can help you get back on track.

Note that we are testing keyboard focus order and management within a component, not page-level navigation– we’ll do that later with Cypress Integration Testing!

🛠 Solution: Test Reaching Submenu Items

First, create an it statement with a string description of the expected behavior of being able to reach open submenu items.

I’m going to use a similar selector to what I used in the first test but this time I’ll select the second menu button for variety. Pass the selector for megamenu-section2 into cy.get, then focus and click to activate the menu section.

Here’s what my solution looks like so far:

it('should reach open submenu items with the keyboard', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section2"]').focus().click()
		
		

    })
  })
it('should reach open submenu items with the keyboard', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section2"]').focus().click()
		
		

    })
  })

Now that Cypress focused and clicked on the menu button, it should be open. So if the Tab key is pressed, focus should shift to the first link in the submenu.

Recall from the SubNavLinkGroup component that each link is assigned a data-testid by interpolating its index as it is mapped over.

Each menu item’s first link will have the same data-testid of link-0. This is fine for our demo app. For a production app, consider making test ids unique across component instances to avoid unintentionally focusing on the wrong element.

I’ll write the expectation that the element has the correct attribute the same way as in the previous test:

it('should reach open submenu items with the keyboard', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section2"]').focus().click()

    cy.focused().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().then(($el) => {
      expect($el).to.have.attr('data-testid', 'link-0')
    })
  })
it('should reach open submenu items with the keyboard', () => {
    cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section2"]').focus().click()

    cy.focused().realPress('Tab')

    cy.focused().then(($el) => {
      expect($el).to.have.attr('data-testid', 'link-0')
    })
  })

Running the test in Cypress shows us that the test passes, and it is able to find the first link.
